To solidify Hong Kong’s status as an Asia-Pacific fintech hub, the HKMA continues to implement measures that promote technological development and application in the banking and payments sectors. Major progress within the year includes:
- Promoting broader adoption of the Faster Payment System "FPS";
- Advancing open application programming interfaces (Open APIs) implementation among banks;
- Connecting the trade finance platform "eTradeConnect" with the People's Bank of China’s (PBOC) trade finance blockchain platform, facilitating digitalisation of trade finance;
- Conducting research on the application of central bank digital currencies (CBDC) for cross-border payments;
- Exploring the technical feasibility of the "Commercial Data Interchange" and developing new types of credit scoring models to help SMEs access financing;
- Announcing a two-year plan to develop a more scalable and diversified regtech ecosystem, further promoting regtech applications;
- Strengthening talent cultivation; and
- Promoting cross-border fintech collaboration.

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee sets the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(a) To safeguard capital;
(b) To ensure that the overall monetary base at all times is fully supported by highly liquid US dollar assets;
(c) To ensure that liquidity is sufficient to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(d) To maximize investment returns consistent with the above (a) to (c), thereby safeguarding the long-term purchasing power of the Fund.

- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud or error, design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks, and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to provide a basis for my opinion. The risk of not detecting a material misstatement due to fraud is higher than for one due to error, as fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, false statements, or override of internal controls;
- Understand internal control relevant to the audit to design appropriate audit procedures, but not to express an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group’s internal control;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Financial Management Officer are appropriate and whether the accounting estimates and related disclosures are reasonable;
- Conclude on whether there is a material uncertainty related to events or conditions that may cast significant doubt on the Group’s ability to continue as a going concern, and, if such a material uncertainty exists, to require adequate disclosure in the financial statements. If disclosures are inadequate, I am required to withdraw from issuing an unmodified opinion or to modify my opinion. My conclusions are based on audit evidence obtained up to the date of my auditor’s report. However, future events or conditions may cause the Group to cease to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including disclosures, and whether the financial statements represent the underlying transactions and events fairly;
- Obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of the entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for overseeing, directing, and performing the group audit. I bear all consequences for my auditor’s opinion.
